WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:27.928
<v Casey>A quarter of Vancouver Island handed to a rail baron a hundred and forty years ago, without a single First Nation's consent — that history is back in a new exhibit this week. Arctic communities are co-mapping their own permafrost data with scientists right now. And we're asking the harder question underneath both: when a map gets built "together," who actually holds the pen?

00:00:53.228 --> 00:01:15.085
<v Casey>Welcome to Cariboo Signals, an AI-generated review of the latest tech news and ideas that impact our rural communities. It's Thursday, July 9th, 2026. Here in the Cariboo, on the traditional and unceded territories of the Secwépemc, Tŝilhqot'in, and Dakelh nations. Today's theme is Indigenous Lands and Innovation — I'm Casey.

00:01:15.385 --> 00:01:28.242
<v Riley>And I'm Riley. We're looking at where technology serves community sovereignty instead of quietly replacing it — and, just as often today, where the two get confused with each other.

00:01:28.542 --> 00:01:45.256
<v Casey>Quick weather check before we get into it — Horsefly Lake is sitting at 10 degrees this morning with mainly clear skies, high of 20, low of 9, with moderate rain moving in tomorrow, around 4 millimetres of precipitation.

00:01:45.556 --> 00:02:01.841
<v Riley>Across the rest of the region — 100 Mile House is at 8, Williams Lake and Quesnel both sitting at 10, all mainly clear. Out on the Chilcotin plateau, Alexis Creek is at 9 under overcast skies today.

00:02:02.641 --> 00:02:05.212
<v Casey>Let's get into what's actually happening.

00:02:06.712 --> 00:02:38.426
<v Riley>Start in the Arctic, where researchers on the Permafrost Pathways project are working directly with Indigenous partners to turn spatial data into a governance tool. The project tracks thaw, erosion, and infrastructure risk across northern territory, but the framing that matters is that Indigenous partners are described as coproducing the datasets — shaping what gets measured and how it gets used — rather than being consulted after scientists have already decided what to track.

00:02:38.726 --> 00:02:46.868
<v Casey>Coproduced is a specific word choice, and we'll come back to what it actually guarantees in the Deep Dive.

00:02:47.168 --> 00:03:12.882
<v Riley>There's a companion piece circulating this week — badly garbled in our feed, unfortunately, but the headline comes through clearly. Researchers from the Arctic to Australia are demanding respect for Indigenous data, which tells you this isn't a one-region problem. It's the same fight over who owns information collected about a territory, playing out on two different continents at once.

00:03:13.982 --> 00:03:37.124
<v Casey>Closer to home — Kamloops-based Interior Indigenous Community Futures has a new name and what executive director George Casimir is calling a new chapter for the organization. It's part rebrand, part signal about how the group sees its own evolution, moving from a narrower economic development mandate toward something broader across the BC Interior.

00:03:37.424 --> 00:03:41.709
<v Riley>Rebrands are cheap. What actually changed in the mandate itself?

00:03:42.009 --> 00:04:00.009
<v Casey>The interview frames it as reflecting growth the organization has already done — expanded programming, wider regional reach — rather than a shift that's still coming. Whether the funding structure grew with it is the thing worth tracking over the next year.

00:04:01.509 --> 00:04:19.080
<v Riley>Down in the Okanagan, the Osoyoos Indian Band and the provincial government have started negotiations and public engagement toward a reconciliation agreement. BC's release frames this as engagement shaping the deal before it's finalized, not a comment period bolted on afterward.

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:27.094
<v Casey>Before, in theory. We've all seen "engagement" mean a suggestion box after the real decisions are locked in.

00:04:27.394 --> 00:04:56.536
<v Riley>The Osoyoos Indian Band isn't waiting to find out either way. They're already moving ahead independently, restoring forest burned in the 2021 Nk'Mip fire — replanting native species, berries, and medicinal plants instead of a standard commercial reforestation mix, specifically to bring back biodiversity and wildlife. That's a Nation setting its own land management priorities right now, on the ground, regardless of what the reconciliation talks eventually produce.

00:04:56.836 --> 00:05:07.550
<v Casey>That's honestly the more interesting story of the two — self-determined land stewardship moving ahead of the formal governance process instead of waiting on it.

00:05:08.750 --> 00:05:31.892
<v Riley>In Ontario, Aamjiwnaang First Nation is calling on the Crown to, in their words, immediately initiate engagement over a proposed west-to-east pipeline. They're not opposing the project outright at this stage — they're insisting the conversation happen before routing decisions get locked in, which is exactly the sequencing problem Casey just flagged with Osoyoos.

00:05:32.192 --> 00:05:39.477
<v Casey>Same ask, different province, different level of government: talk to us before the map is already drawn.

00:05:39.777 --> 00:06:04.634
<v Riley>And that phrase is almost literal in a story out of Victoria this week. The Tyee has coverage of a new exhibit spotlighting what's being called the land grab that handed a full quarter of Vancouver Island to a rail baron — a grant made a hundred and forty years ago without any First Nations' consent at all.

00:06:05.434 --> 00:06:23.005
<v Casey>That's not tucked-away history, either. The Esquimalt and Nanaimo Railway land grant is still tangled up in active title claims today. A hundred and forty years later, the map from that original deal is still the document courts are arguing over.

00:06:23.305 --> 00:06:38.304
<v Riley>Which is the thread sitting under half of today's roundup — who draws the map, and whether consultation after the fact is worth much of anything if the boundaries were already set before anyone asked.

00:06:38.604 --> 00:06:47.175
<v Casey>We'll dig into that properly in the Deep Dive. A few other stories worth a mention before we move on.

00:06:47.475 --> 00:07:12.332
<v Riley>Harvard engineers have turned a silicon chip into a DNA-writing machine — synthesizing dozens of sequences simultaneously using electricity and water-based enzymes instead of the usual chemical process. It's cleaner, and over time it could meaningfully shrink the cost of genomics research, which matters for any lab doing conservation or wildlife genetics work outside a major urban centre.

00:07:12.632 --> 00:07:31.489
<v Casey>Business Insider flagged a Morgan Stanley bond manager warning that Big Tech's AI debt binge — companies flooding the market with bonds to fund data centre buildout — is starting to look shaky. Worth watching given how much of that buildout touches BC directly.

00:07:31.789 --> 00:07:54.074
<v Riley>Speaking of which — half of parents surveyed in another Business Insider piece this week say they're worried their kids are too attached to AI tools. Not a Cariboo-specific number, but a trend every school district here is going to run into eventually, whether it shows up in a survey or not.

00:07:54.374 --> 00:08:14.945
<v Casey>And on the wildfire front, since fire season is back with us — CFJC Today reports the Boston Bar–area fires have exploded in size, with alerts now stretching into the Thompson-Nicola Regional District. Nothing new in terms of a system failure, just a reminder the season's already serious.

00:08:15.245 --> 00:08:30.673
<v Riley>On a lighter note, Boing Boing dug up a 1990 internet standard, RFC 1149, for carrying data by homing pigeon. Latency's terrible, but the bandwidth-per-bird is apparently not bad if you strap on enough memory cards.

00:08:31.373 --> 00:08:34.801
<v Casey>There's a rural broadband joke in there somewhere.

00:08:35.101 --> 00:08:57.815
<v Riley>There really is. Also on the science side this week — WIRED reports a mystery compound detected on both Pluto and Titan that doesn't match anything in existing spectroscopic databases. And Blue Origin says it's aiming to relaunch New Glenn later this year, working to recover from the rocket's explosion back in May.

00:08:58.115 --> 00:09:13.114
<v Casey>New Atlas also has researchers filming a goblin shark alive in the deep ocean for the first time ever, which expands what we know about its range and depth. Small thing, but a genuine first.

00:09:13.414 --> 00:09:31.842
<v Riley>And ScienceDaily has a less charming one — a spike in poison control calls tied to accidental Ozempic and Wegovy dosing mistakes, as semaglutide use has climbed. Not a rural-specific story, but a reminder that rapid drug adoption outpaces patient education fairly often.

00:09:32.142 --> 00:09:41.570
<v Casey>That's a fair stack of stories for today. Let's talk about the Cariboo Friendship Society before we get into the Deep Dive.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:10:09.727
<v Casey>The Cariboo Friendship Society has been serving the urban Indigenous community in this region since 1969 — housing support, youth programs, crisis services, and The Hearth restaurant, which doubles as both a meal program and a genuine gathering space for people who need one. Fifty-plus years of continuous operation in this region is not a small thing, and it's not something that happens by accident.

00:10:10.027 --> 00:10:18.598
<v Riley>That kind of longevity says something about community trust that a five-year pilot program never gets the chance to build.

00:10:18.898 --> 00:10:38.612
<v Casey>If you want to learn more or support their work, find them at cariboofriendshipsociety dot ca. And that idea — an institution communities trust because it's been there through decades, not through a single grant cycle — is a good frame heading into today's Deep Dive.

00:10:39.812 --> 00:11:01.240
<v Riley>The word doing the heavy lifting across half of today's stories is "coproduced." The Permafrost Pathways project describes its Arctic maps that way — built with Indigenous partners, not just about them. The question worth sitting with is what coproduced actually guarantees, versus what it just sounds like it guarantees.

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:16.968
<v Casey>It sounds like partnership. In practice, it often means the outside institution still owns the server, still owns the publication, and still decides which version of the map gets cited when an environmental assessment comes due.

00:11:17.268 --> 00:11:38.268
<v Riley>The Permafrost Pathways framing is more specific than that, though. Participants are described as transforming spatial data into a tool for empowerment, which suggests Indigenous partners are shaping what gets tracked in the first place — not just supplying local knowledge to fill gaps in someone else's predetermined dataset.

00:11:38.568 --> 00:12:03.853
<v Casey>Shaping what gets tracked isn't the same as controlling what happens to the data afterward. Who hosts it? Who can query it in five years, when a mining company argues an access road doesn't actually cross sensitive permafrost? That's the OCAP question — ownership, control, access, possession — and "coproduced" doesn't answer any of the four on its own.

00:12:04.653 --> 00:12:29.510
<v Riley>It's fair to leave that question open, because the article genuinely doesn't say. But mapping specifically matters more than most data categories here, because a map isn't just information. It's a governance instrument. It's the thing courts, regulators, and companies point to when they decide where a pipeline goes or where a reconciliation agreement's boundary line actually falls.

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:55.952
<v Casey>Which is exactly why the Vancouver Island story lands so hard today. A map drawn a hundred and forty years ago — the Esquimalt and Nanaimo land grant — is still the document being argued over in title claims right now. Nobody consulted anyone when that map was made, and the consequences are still live a century and a half later.

00:12:56.252 --> 00:13:15.966
<v Riley>That's the case for coproduction mattering, not against it. If the map made today is built with the Nation actually controlling the underlying data, that's a fundamentally different legal artifact fifty years from now than one imposed entirely from outside, the way the E&N grant was.

00:13:16.266 --> 00:13:37.266
<v Casey>Only if control genuinely sits with the Nation from the start. Otherwise you've just built a more polite version of the same instrument — one that photographs well in a press release and still ends up owned by whoever hosts the database when the dispute finally reaches a courtroom.

00:13:38.266 --> 00:14:03.980
<v Riley>Look at the Osoyoos reconciliation talks announced this week. The province is framing public engagement as happening at the beginning of the process, shaping the agreement before it's finalized — that's structurally different from a comment period bolted onto a signed deal. Sequencing is a design choice, and this time the choice was apparently made correctly, at least on paper.

00:14:04.280 --> 00:14:26.994
<v Casey>On paper. Aamjiwnaang First Nation, in the exact same week, is having to publicly demand that identical sequencing from the federal Crown on a pipeline — engage with us before the routing decision, not after. If engagement-first were genuinely becoming standard practice, Aamjiwnaang wouldn't need to ask for it as a special concession.

00:14:27.294 --> 00:14:46.151
<v Riley>Different level of government, different regulatory track — pipeline approvals move through federal processes with their own institutional inertia, and that inertia predates this week by decades. That's not evidence the model failed. It's evidence the model hasn't been adopted uniformly across jurisdictions yet.

00:14:46.451 --> 00:15:16.879
<v Casey>Which is the same unresolved thing this theme keeps landing on, episode after episode. A good practice in one negotiation doesn't automatically travel to the next one. There's no enforcement mechanism that makes engagement-first the default — it gets renegotiated case by case, Nation by Nation, government by government. That's exhausting to sustain over the course of decades, and exhausting is exactly the point where these efforts tend to quietly stop.

00:15:17.779 --> 00:15:45.636
<v Riley>The Osoyoos Indian Band isn't waiting on that enforcement question to resolve itself, though. They're restoring the Nk'Mip fire area on their own terms right now — their own species selection, their own priorities, independent of whatever the reconciliation agreement eventually says. That's not asking permission to be consulted. That's a Nation exercising land management authority it already holds, on the ground, in real time.

00:15:45.936 --> 00:16:07.793
<v Casey>That's the version of self-determination that actually holds up under pressure — action taken because the authority already exists, not because it was granted through a consultation process. It's a genuinely different category from the Permafrost Pathways maps, where the authority question is still open and unresolved in the public materials.

00:16:08.593 --> 00:16:29.593
<v Riley>— and it's worth being straight about something here: we're working from published project descriptions and government releases, not conversations with communications staff from any of these Nations directly, so what "coproduced" means in day-to-day practice may be more settled on the ground than the public documents let on.

00:16:29.893 --> 00:16:44.892
<v Casey>Fair to flag. It cuts the other way too, though — the public materials might just as easily be overselling the collaboration because it makes for a better headline than the actual arrangement underneath it.

00:16:45.192 --> 00:17:17.334
<v Riley>Either way, there's a concrete thing communities here could actually test for themselves. If a Cariboo Nation — one of the Northern Secwépemc communities, say, or a Tŝilhqot'in government already running wildfire or watershed monitoring — wanted to pursue a coproduced dataset with a university or provincial ministry, the negotiation shouldn't start with the science plan. It should start with a written data-hosting and access agreement, settled before a single sensor goes into the ground.

00:17:17.634 --> 00:17:36.919
<v Casey>That's essentially the Denisiqi model we've talked about before — governance negotiated before delivery begins, not retrofitted after the fact. Twenty-plus years of operational continuity there came from communities insisting on control from day one. Not because a funder happened to design it that way.

00:17:37.219 --> 00:18:02.076
<v Riley>Right, and the reason it's worth restating in a different context is that the principle applies just as much to a permafrost sensor network as it does to a social services agency. The instrument changes — data instead of a building, a server instead of a facility — but the governance question underneath it doesn't change at all.

00:18:02.976 --> 00:18:31.261
<v Casey>Where this consistently gets stuck is funding. Even a well-governed dataset needs someone paying for server costs, ongoing maintenance, staff time to keep access controls current and enforced. If that money comes from the same province or federal ministry the data might eventually be used to challenge in a hearing, you're right back in the accountability bind we've hit on this theme more than once already.

00:18:31.561 --> 00:19:07.989
<v Riley>Which is where the more interesting move isn't chasing a bigger grant — it's changing who's structurally obligated to fund the thing in the first place. If a Nation's dataset becomes the reference a regulator is legally required to consult before approving development on that territory, the funding relationship flips entirely. The Nation isn't asking for money to build a nice-to-have map anymore. The regulator needs that map to do its job. That's leverage, not charity, and leverage doesn't evaporate when a grant cycle ends.

00:19:08.289 --> 00:19:41.717
<v Casey>That only works once the map is actually adopted as the legal reference point, and that hasn't happened here yet. The Reciprocal Research Network we've discussed before got there through literal decades of relationship-building between BC First Nations and the UBC Museum of Anthropology — not through a fast policy fix anyone could replicate on a five-year timeline. Small comfort if your Nation is trying to get something built in the next five years, not the next twenty-five.

00:19:42.017 --> 00:20:11.588
<v Riley>True. But the Interior Indigenous Community Futures rebrand this week is a small, concrete example of an organization actively trying to reposition itself for exactly that kind of broader, standing mandate — moving past narrow project-based economic development funding toward something with more institutional weight behind it. Whether the money and the authority actually follow the new name is the open question nobody outside the organization can answer yet.

00:20:12.388 --> 00:20:34.673
<v Casey>It always is. The Vancouver Island exhibit is a useful gut check to hold onto here, though. A hundred and forty years from now, will today's coproduced datasets look like genuine partnership? Or will they look like another carefully documented arrangement that quietly ended up favoring whoever happened to control the server?

00:20:34.973 --> 00:20:53.401
<v Riley>The honest answer is it depends entirely on whether Nations hold the access controls now, while these projects are still new and the precedents are still being set — not on whether this week's press release used the right vocabulary to describe them.

00:20:53.701 --> 00:21:10.843
<v Casey>That's the actual test, then. Not the word "coproduced." Who can revoke access. Who gets a say when the dataset is subpoenaed, licensed, or quietly folded into a provincial database five years from now without anyone circling back to ask.

00:21:11.143 --> 00:21:30.428
<v Riley>And that's not a hypothetical for the Cariboo specifically — it's the exact question any Nation here should be asking before signing onto a university partnership, a provincial monitoring program, or a data-sharing agreement tied to wildfire or watershed work already underway in this region.

00:21:31.328 --> 00:21:58.756
<v Casey>Worth raising directly at a band council meeting or a regional forestry table, if anyone listening is in a position to ask it: before the sensors go in, before the researchers arrive with their grant already approved — who signs off on what happens to this data in year six, when nobody currently in the room is still around to remember what was promised.

00:21:59.756 --> 00:22:25.898
<v Riley>If you're part of a Cariboo Nation or community organization working through exactly this kind of data agreement, or if you've got a correction on how we characterized anything today, the door's open — feedback at cariboo signals dot c-a. We'd genuinely like to hear how the access question actually gets negotiated on the ground, not just in a press release.

00:22:26.198 --> 00:22:47.198
<v Casey>And before we go — full transparency, everything in today's episode came from public reporting and government releases. We haven't sat down with communications staff from any of the Nations named today, so if we got the framing wrong somewhere, that's precisely the kind of correction we're asking for.

00:22:47.498 --> 00:22:50.497
<v Riley>Have a great rest of your day.

00:22:50.797 --> 00:22:53.796
<v Casey>Have a great rest of your day.